<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-471-820  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 471 820.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 18 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hong Kong police computerize.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Worsley, Michael; Roowi, S.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   SAS Institute Inc. (product development).andO;Product:   DEC VAX 6210 (Minicomputer) (usage)Oracle (Data base management system) (usage).andO;Topic:     Hong KongLaw EnforcementData Management.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>HONG KONG POLICE COMPUTERIZE HONG KONG, ASIA, 1989 JUL 7 (NB) -- Hong Kong'scrime-fighting departments are using more efficient forms of recording datawith software supplied by the SAS Institute, according to a report inComputerworld.andP;  Two SAS software modules control the government's IntegratedLaw and Order Statistical System (ILOSS), which was developed for thesecurity branch by the Government Data Processing Agency (GDPA).andP;  &quot;ILOSSrecords data on offences, offenders and their progress  through the criminaljustice system,&quot; said SM Yip, project manager with the GDPA Euphemia, whendescribing some of the different functions of the software.andP;  The softwareruns on a DEC VAX 6210 with a 3G-byte hard disk and is interfaced with theOracle database system.andP;  ILOSS produces reports for use in policy planning byseveral departments such as the police, judiciary, correctional services andsocial welfare departments.andP;  It can be used to plot crime trends and generatemonthly fixed format reports for the police brief to the Executive Council.andO;(Michael Worsley andamp; S.Roowi/19890714)</TEXT></DOC>